---
import Site from '../../layouts/Site.astro';

const sections = [
  { id: 'getting-started', label: 'Getting Started' },
  { id: 'worktrees', label: 'Worktree Isolation' },
  { id: 'kanban', label: 'Kanban Board' },
  { id: 'terminals', label: 'Terminal Sessions' },
  { id: 'sandbox', label: 'VM Sandbox' },
  { id: 'hooks', label: 'Hooks' },
  { id: 'claude-code', label: 'Claude Code' },
  { id: 'cli', label: 'CLI' },
];
---
<Site title="Documentation · Ouijit" description="Ouijit documentation: getting started, worktrees, kanban, terminals, VM sandbox, hooks, and Claude Code integration.">
  <div class="docs-layout">
    <aside class="docs-sidebar">
      <h4>Documentation</h4>
      <ul>
        {sections.map((s) => (
          <li>
            <a href={`#${s.id}`} data-doc-link={s.id}>{s.label}</a>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </aside>
    <main class="docs-content">
      <section id="getting-started">
        <h1>Getting Started</h1>
        <p class="lead">Install Ouijit and launch your first project in under a minute.</p>

        <h2>Requirements</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>macOS</strong> 13+ (Ventura) or <strong>Linux</strong> (x64)</li>
          <li><strong>Git</strong> 2.20+</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Download &amp; Install</h2>
        <p>Download the latest release for your platform:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="https://github.com/ouijit/ouijit/releases/latest/download/ouijit-darwin-arm64.zip">macOS (Apple Silicon)</a></li>
          <li><a href="https://github.com/ouijit/ouijit/releases/latest/download/ouijit-darwin-x64.zip">macOS (Intel)</a></li>
          <li><a href="https://github.com/ouijit/ouijit/releases/latest/download/ouijit-linux-x64.zip">Linux (x64)</a></li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Unzip the archive and move <strong>Ouijit.app</strong> to your Applications folder (macOS) or extract the binary to
          a location on your PATH (Linux).
        </p>

        <h3>Building from source</h3>
        <p>Requires Node.js 20+ and C/C++ build tools for native modules (better-sqlite3, node-pty, koffi):</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>macOS:</strong> <code>xcode-select --install</code></li>
          <li><strong>Linux:</strong> <code>sudo apt install build-essential python3</code></li>
        </ul>
        <pre><code>git clone https://github.com/ouijit/ouijit.git
cd ouijit
npm install
npm start</code></pre>

        <h2>First Launch</h2>
        <p>
          When you first open Ouijit you'll see the <strong>home view</strong> with a sidebar listing your projects on the
          left. The main area shows terminal sessions grouped by project, empty on first launch until you add a project and
          start working.
        </p>

        <h3>Adding a project</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Click the <strong>+</strong> button in the sidebar.</li>
          <li>Select a folder containing a git repository.</li>
          <li>That's it. Your project appears in the list.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Opening a project</h3>
        <p>Click any project to open it. You'll start on the kanban board, and opening a task launches its terminal.</p>
      </section>

      <section id="worktrees">
        <h1>Worktree Isolation</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          Every task gets its own git worktree, so you can work on multiple features simultaneously without branch switching.
        </p>

        <h2>What are git worktrees?</h2>
        <p>
          Git worktrees let you check out multiple branches of the same repository into separate directories at the same
          time. Instead of stashing changes and switching branches, each worktree has its own working directory with its own
          checked-out branch.
        </p>
        <p>Ouijit creates a worktree when you start a task, so each piece of work gets its own directory and branch.</p>

        <h2>How Ouijit uses worktrees</h2>
        <h3>Task lifecycle</h3>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Create task</strong>. A new branch is created from your main branch (e.g. <code>T-42</code>).</li>
          <li>
            <strong>Start task</strong>. Ouijit creates a git worktree under <code>~/Ouijit/worktrees/</code>. The terminal
            opens in this isolated directory.
          </li>
          <li><strong>Work</strong>. All changes happen in the worktree. Your main branch stays clean.</li>
          <li><strong>Review</strong>. Use the diff panel to see what changed relative to main.</li>
          <li><strong>Complete</strong>. Merge locally, push for a PR, or follow your team's workflow.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          Each of these transitions can trigger <a href="#hooks">lifecycle hooks</a>: scripts that run automatically when a
          task changes status.
        </p>

        <h2>Copy-on-Write cloning</h2>
        <p>
          Creating a full copy of a large repository for each task would be slow and waste disk space. Ouijit uses
          <strong>Copy-on-Write (CoW) cloning</strong> via the native file system (APFS on macOS, reflinks on Linux with
          btrfs/XFS).
        </p>
        <p>CoW clones are nearly instant and share disk blocks with the original until a file is modified. This means:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Worktree creation is fast regardless of repo size</li>
          <li>Disk usage is proportional to your actual changes, not the full repo</li>
          <li>Dependency directories and other git-ignored files are cloned too, so you're ready to work immediately</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Directory structure</h2>
        <pre><code>~/Ouijit/worktrees/
  my-project/
    T-42/                # Worktree for task 42
    T-43/                # Worktree for task 43</code></pre>
        <p>Worktrees live under <code>~/Ouijit/worktrees/</code>, organized by project name.</p>

        <h2>Manual worktree operations</h2>
        <p>
          Ouijit manages worktrees for you, but they're standard git worktrees. You can inspect them with regular git
          commands:
        </p>
        <pre><code># List all worktrees
git worktree list

# From inside a worktree, check which branch it's on
git branch --show-current</code></pre>
      </section>

      <section id="kanban">
        <h1>Kanban Board</h1>
        <p class="lead">A four-column board for organizing tasks with drag-and-drop.</p>

        <h2>Columns</h2>
        <p>The board has four fixed columns that map to a task's lifecycle:</p>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Column</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>To Do</strong></td><td>Planned work. No worktree or branch created yet.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>In Progress</strong></td><td>Active work. A worktree and branch are created when a task moves here.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>In Review</strong></td><td>Work is done, ready for review. Worktree is still active.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Done</strong></td><td>Completed. The branch can be merged and the worktree removed.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>Moving a task between columns triggers <a href="#hooks">lifecycle hooks</a>: scripts that can do anything, such as running tests, opening a PR, or kicking off an agent.</p>

        <h2>Creating tasks</h2>
        <p>Click the <strong>+</strong> button on any column header, or press <code>⌘N</code> (<code>Ctrl+N</code> on Linux) to create a new task. Give it a title and optional description.</p>
        <p>Each task gets an auto-incrementing number (e.g. <code>T-1</code>, <code>T-2</code>) used for branch names and worktree directories.</p>

        <h2>Drag and drop</h2>
        <p>Drag task cards between columns to change their status. You can also reorder tasks within a column.</p>
        <p>When dragging a task from <strong>To Do</strong> to <strong>In Progress</strong>, Ouijit automatically creates a git worktree and branch for the task.</p>

        <h2>Task actions</h2>
        <p>Right-click a task card to access its context menu:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Open in Terminal</strong>. Launch a terminal in the task's worktree.</li>
          <li><strong>Open in Sandbox</strong>. Launch a sandboxed terminal (if Lima is available).</li>
          <li><strong>Open in Editor</strong>. Open the worktree in your configured editor.</li>
          <li><strong>Rename</strong>. Edit the task's display name inline.</li>
          <li><strong>Move to Done / Reopen</strong>. Complete an active task or reopen a finished one.</li>
          <li><strong>Delete</strong>. Permanently remove the task.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>If a task already has running terminals, they'll appear at the top of the menu so you can jump straight to them.</p>
      </section>

      <section id="terminals">
        <h1>Terminal Sessions</h1>
        <p class="lead">Integrated terminal sessions with a card stack UI for multi-terminal workflows.</p>

        <h2>Card stack</h2>
        <p>Terminals are displayed as stacked cards. The active terminal is in front; background terminals peek out behind it so you can see what's running.</p>
        <p>Each terminal is a full PTY session running your default shell, opened in the task's worktree directory.</p>

        <h2>Opening terminals</h2>
        <p>When you start a task (move it to In Progress), a terminal opens automatically in the task's worktree. You can open additional terminals for the same task: one for a dev server, one for an editor, one for an agent, or any combination you need.</p>

        <h2>Keyboard shortcuts</h2>
        <p>Click on a background terminal card to bring it to the front, or use keyboard shortcuts:</p>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Shortcut</th><th>Action</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>⌘I</code> / <code>Ctrl+I</code></td><td>New terminal</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>⌘W</code> / <code>Ctrl+W</code></td><td>Close terminal</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>⌘1</code>–<code>⌘9</code> / <code>Ctrl+1</code>–<code>Ctrl+9</code></td><td>Select terminal by position</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>⌘⇧←</code> / <code>Ctrl+Shift+Left</code></td><td>Previous stack page</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>⌘⇧→</code> / <code>Ctrl+Shift+Right</code></td><td>Next stack page</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>⌘T</code> / <code>Ctrl+T</code></td><td>Toggle between kanban board and terminal stack</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>⌘N</code> / <code>Ctrl+N</code></td><td>Show kanban board and focus new task input</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>⌘P</code> / <code>Ctrl+P</code></td><td>Toggle runner panel</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>⌘D</code> / <code>Ctrl+D</code></td><td>Toggle diff panel</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <h2>Runner panel</h2>
        <p>The runner panel is a secondary terminal that sits alongside your main terminal stack. It's meant for long-running processes like dev servers: things you want visible but out of the way.</p>
        <p>Toggle it with <code>⌘P</code> (<code>Ctrl+P</code> on Linux), or use the Run button in the toolbar. The runner executes the project's <strong>run</strong> <a href="#hooks">hook</a> (e.g. <code>npm run dev</code>), so you can start your dev server with one click or keypress.</p>

        <h2>Diff panel</h2>
        <p>The diff panel shows what changed in the current worktree relative to the target branch. Toggle it with <code>⌘D</code> (<code>Ctrl+D</code> on Linux).</p>
        <p>It lists changed files with per-file diffs organized by hunk: additions, deletions, and context lines. Useful for a quick review before moving a task to In Review or merging.</p>

        <h2>Tags</h2>
        <p>You can tag terminals to organize them, especially useful in the home view when you have many terminals across projects. Tags appear on terminal cards and you can group the home view by tag.</p>

        <h2>Working with CLI agents</h2>
        <p>Ouijit's terminals work with any CLI tool. Launch Claude Code, Cursor, Aider, or any other agent directly in the terminal. Worktree isolation means each agent works in its own sandbox without interfering with other tasks. <a href="#claude-code">Claude Code gets live status indicators</a>; other agents run normally without them.</p>
      </section>

      <section id="sandbox">
        <h1>VM Sandbox</h1>
        <p class="lead">Run terminal sessions inside a lightweight Linux VM so agents can't touch what they shouldn't.</p>

        <h2>Why sandbox?</h2>
        <p>Git worktrees isolate your code, but a terminal session still has full access to your host: your home directory, credentials, system binaries, network. When CLI agents run arbitrary commands, that's a lot of trust.</p>
        <p>The VM sandbox wraps each terminal in a <a href="https://lima-vm.io" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Lima</a> virtual machine. Your project worktree is mounted into the VM (read-write), but the rest of your filesystem is walled off. Inside the worktree, every path your <code>.gitignore</code> matches, like <code>.env</code> files, <code>secrets/</code>, <code>node_modules</code>, build artifacts, is masked with an empty placeholder so the agent only sees what git would track. The agent can install packages, run builds, and execute code without risk to your host or your host-only secrets.</p>

        <h2>How it works</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Enable sandbox on a task</strong>. Sandboxing is per-task, not per-project. When you start or continue a task, the run dialog has a <strong>Sandbox</strong> toggle. Flip it on and the task's terminal will spawn inside the VM.</li>
          <li><strong>First terminal</strong>. Ouijit lazily creates an Ubuntu 24.04 VM via Lima on the first sandboxed spawn for a project. One VM per project, shared across that project's sandboxed tasks. Subsequent terminals reuse the running VM.</li>
          <li><strong>Spawn progress</strong>. The spawn dialog shows each step: checking VM status, creating / starting, SSH connect, provisioning, isolating gitignored paths, launching shell. First boot takes a minute or two; later spawns are fast.</li>
          <li><strong>Shell sessions</strong>. Terminals run inside the VM via <code>limactl shell</code>. Your worktree is mounted at the same path as on the host, so relative paths and git operations work normally.</li>
          <li><strong>VM lifecycle &amp; resources</strong>. Manage the VM from <strong>Project Settings → Sandbox</strong>. You can see the VM status (Running / Stopped / Broken / Not created), create, start, stop, or recreate it, open a VM console, and edit the merged Lima YAML config (memory, CPU, disk, mounts). Changing resources prompts you to recreate the VM.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2>What's isolated</h2>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Resource</th><th>Host terminal</th><th>Sandboxed terminal</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Project worktree</td><td>Read/write</td><td>Read/write (mounted)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Main repo</td><td>Read/write</td><td>Read-only (mounted)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Home directory</td><td>Full access</td><td>Ephemeral VM home</td></tr>
            <tr><td>System files</td><td>Full access</td><td>Isolated (Ubuntu guest)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Network</td><td>Host network</td><td>NAT (macOS) or user-mode (Linux)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Processes</td><td>Can see/kill all</td><td>VM processes only</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h2>Gitignored paths are masked</h2>
        <p>When a sandboxed terminal starts, every path your <code>.gitignore</code> matches is replaced with an empty placeholder inside the VM. Host-only secrets like <code>.env</code> or <code>config/secrets.yml</code> aren't visible to the agent, and platform-specific artifacts like macOS <code>node_modules</code> don't leak into the Linux guest.</p>
        <p>There's no config file or allowlist to maintain. Ouijit runs <code>git ls-files</code> against the worktree and honors whatever git says is ignored: negations (<code>!keep.env</code>), nested <code>.gitignore</code> files, globs, and <code>core.excludesFile</code> all work. The terminal startup banner reports what was hidden, e.g. <em>"Isolating 12 paths (7 dir, 5 file)"</em>.</p>

        <h3>What this buys you</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Secret isolation</strong>. Gitignored <code>.env</code>, <code>.npmrc</code>, <code>secrets/</code>, and similar files stay on the host.</li>
          <li><strong>No ABI mismatches</strong>. darwin-arm64 <code>node_modules</code>, Rust <code>target/</code>, and Python <code>.venv</code> never collide with the Linux guest's toolchain.</li>
          <li><strong>Per-task isolation</strong>. Two parallel sandboxed tasks on the same project can't stomp each other's installs.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Caveats</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Committed files are always visible.</strong> <code>.gitignore</code> only affects files git considers untracked. If you committed a secret and then gitignored it, the agent still sees it. Run <code>git rm --cached &lt;file&gt;</code> and rotate the secret. Don't commit what you don't want an agent to read.</li>
          <li><strong>Masking is a snapshot at terminal start.</strong> New gitignored files created while a terminal is already open aren't masked in that terminal. Close and reopen to re-enumerate.</li>
          <li><strong>Filenames aren't hidden, only contents.</strong> <code>ls</code> still shows <code>.env.secrets</code> as a 0-byte file. Don't rely on this to hide secret-sounding paths.</li>
          <li><strong>The worktree is read-write.</strong> The VM has no git credentials, so a compromised agent can't push, but it can stage commits that a human on the host could unknowingly push later. Review diffs before pushing.</li>
          <li><strong>Scope is the worktree.</strong> Files in the VM's own <code>$HOME</code> (e.g. <code>~/.netrc</code>, <code>~/.git-credentials</code>) aren't covered. Lima ships a clean home; don't copy host auth into it.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Startup banners</h3>
        <p>Masking is fail-closed: if isolation can't be delivered, the terminal refuses to start. Every spawn resolves to one of three banners, printed to the terminal before the interactive shell:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>SANDBOX ISOLATION ACTIVE</strong>. Green. Masks applied. Shell starts.</li>
          <li><strong>SANDBOX NO PATHS TO ISOLATE</strong>. Yellow. Nothing was gitignored in the worktree. Shell still starts. Double-check your <code>.gitignore</code> before running anything sensitive.</li>
          <li><strong>SANDBOX ISOLATION FAILED</strong>. Red. Enumeration error, missing sudo, mount failure, or any partial failure. The shell exits immediately; fix the cause and reopen. Partial failures are treated as total failures.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Errors that happen before the VM side runs (e.g. <code>git ls-files</code> throws) come back as a failed terminal-open in Ouijit, not as a banner.</p>

        <h2>Customizing the VM</h2>
        <p>VMs start from a clean Ubuntu 24.04 image with <code>bash</code>, <code>git</code>, <code>curl</code>, <code>wget</code>, <code>nodejs</code>, <code>npm</code>, <code>python3</code>, and <code>build-essential</code> pre-installed. Defaults are 4 GiB memory, 2 CPUs, 10 GiB disk.</p>
        <p>Everything else, like resource limits, extra packages, additional mounts, and provisioning scripts, is controlled by the Lima YAML config in <strong>Project Settings → Sandbox</strong>. The editor shows the merged effective config and lets you write overrides; Ouijit prompts you to recreate the VM when changes require it.</p>
        <p>See the <a href="https://lima-vm.io/docs/config/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Lima configuration reference</a> for the available keys.</p>

        <h2>Claude Code integration</h2>
        <p>Ouijit automatically injects its hook helper script and Claude Code settings into each sandboxed shell. This means Claude Code's hook status events (thinking, tool use, idle) work inside the VM just like they do on the host: the VM shell communicates back to Ouijit via <code>host.lima.internal</code>.</p>

        <h2>Requirements</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>macOS</strong>. Uses Apple's Virtualization.framework (vz) with vzNAT networking. No extra installation needed if Lima is available.</li>
          <li><strong>Linux</strong>. Uses QEMU with user-mode networking.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Ouijit bundles <code>limactl</code>, so there's nothing extra to install.</p>

        <h2>Limitations</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>First boot downloads an Ubuntu cloud image and provisions packages. Requires internet and takes 1-2 minutes.</li>
          <li>GPU passthrough is not supported.</li>
          <li>macOS-specific tooling (Xcode, Swift) is not available inside the Linux VM.</li>
          <li>Docker-in-VM requires additional Lima configuration.</li>
          <li>The VM home directory is ephemeral. Anything outside mounted directories is lost on recreate.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="hooks">
        <h1>Hooks</h1>
        <p class="lead">Shell commands that run at key moments in a task's lifecycle. Configure per project.</p>

        <h2>Lifecycle hooks</h2>
        <p>These fire when a task changes status. Configure them from the kanban column headers.</p>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Hook</th><th>When it runs</th><th>Example</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>Start</strong></td><td>Task moves from To Do to In Progress</td><td><code>npm install &amp;&amp; claude "$OUIJIT_TASK_PROMPT"</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Continue</strong></td><td>Reopening a task already In Progress</td><td><code>claude -c</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Review</strong></td><td>Task moves to In Review</td><td><code>gh pr create --fill</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Cleanup</strong></td><td>Task moves to Done</td><td><code>git push origin HEAD</code></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h2>Other hooks</h2>
        <p>These run on demand rather than on lifecycle transitions. Configure them from the header bar.</p>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Hook</th><th>What it does</th><th>Example</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>Run</strong></td><td>Command for the Run button (dev server, etc.)</td><td><code>npm run dev</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Editor</strong></td><td>Opens the worktree in your editor</td><td><code>open -a "Visual Studio Code"</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Sandbox Setup</strong></td><td>Runs inside the VM before each terminal command</td><td><code>which claude || npm i -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code</code></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h2>Environment variables</h2>
        <p>Hooks receive context via environment variables so your scripts can act on the current task:</p>
        <pre><code>OUIJIT_PROJECT_PATH=/path/to/my-project
OUIJIT_WORKTREE_PATH=~/Ouijit/worktrees/my-project/T-42
OUIJIT_TASK_BRANCH=T-42
OUIJIT_TASK_NAME="Add user auth"
OUIJIT_TASK_PROMPT="implement oauth login"
OUIJIT_HOOK_TYPE=start</code></pre>

        <h2>What you can do with them</h2>
        <p>Hooks are shell commands, so they can do anything: install dependencies, launch agents, open PRs, run tests. The start hook is especially useful for agent workflows. Set it to <code>claude "$OUIJIT_TASK_PROMPT"</code> and every new task launches an agent with the task description as its prompt.</p>
      </section>

      <section id="claude-code">
        <h1>Claude Code Integration</h1>
        <p class="lead">Live status indicators so you know at a glance which agents are working and which are waiting on you.</p>

        <h2>What you get</h2>
        <p>When Claude Code is running in an Ouijit terminal, the terminal card shows a live status indicator for thinking or idle. Visible across the entire terminal stack, so you can tell which sessions need your attention without bringing each one to the front.</p>

        <h2>How it works</h2>
        <p>Ouijit installs a thin wrapper that shadows the <code>claude</code> command inside its terminals. The wrapper injects hook settings that report status back to Ouijit at runtime. No configuration required: type <code>claude</code> and the integration is active.</p>

        <h2>Notifications</h2>
        <p>When an agent finishes, Ouijit plays a sound. If the window isn't focused, you also get an OS notification.</p>

        <h2>Other agents</h2>
        <p>Ouijit's terminals work with any CLI agent (Cursor, Aider, Codex, and others). They run normally but without the live status indicators. If your agent has a hook or plugin system, <a href="https://github.com/ouijit/ouijit/issues" target="_blank" rel="noopener">open an issue</a>.</p>
      </section>

      <section id="cli">
        <h1>CLI</h1>
        <p class="lead">Drive Ouijit from inside any terminal it spawns. Create tasks, flip statuses, manage hooks, run scripts, all from the shell.</p>

        <h2>Where it lives</h2>
        <p>
          The <code>ouijit</code> command is auto-installed into every terminal Ouijit opens, both host shells and sandboxed
          ones. Nothing to install separately. It communicates with the running app over a localhost API authenticated by a
          per-session token, so it only works from inside an Ouijit terminal.
        </p>

        <h2>Output format</h2>
        <p>
          Every successful command writes a single JSON value to <code>stdout</code> and exits 0. Errors write
          <code>{`{"error": "..."}`}</code> to <code>stderr</code> and exit non-zero. Pipe to <code>jq</code> for grepping
          fields:
        </p>
        <pre><code>ouijit task list | jq '.[] | select(.status == "in_progress") | .name'</code></pre>

        <h2>Project detection</h2>
        <p>
          By default the CLI auto-detects the active project from your current directory by walking up to the nearest git
          root. If you're inside a worktree it follows the <code>.git</code> file back to the main repo. Override with
          <code>--project &lt;path&gt;</code>.
        </p>

        <h2>Tasks</h2>
        <p>Statuses are <code>todo</code>, <code>in_progress</code>, <code>in_review</code>, and <code>done</code>.</p>
        <pre><code>ouijit task list                              # array of tasks
ouijit task get 5                             # single task
ouijit task current                           # task owning this terminal
ouijit task create "Fix login bug"
ouijit task create "Refactor auth" --prompt "Extract middleware"
ouijit task start 5                           # creates worktree, sets in_progress
ouijit task start 5 --branch custom-name
ouijit task create-and-start "Add 2FA"        # create + start in one step
ouijit task set-status 5 in_review
ouijit task set-name 5 "Better name"
ouijit task set-description 5 "More detail"
ouijit task set-merge-target 5 develop
ouijit task delete 5</code></pre>
        <p>
          <code>ouijit task current</code> resolves the task owning the current terminal via the <code>OUIJIT_PTY_ID</code>
          env var that Ouijit sets on every spawn. Useful inside agent scripts:
        </p>
        <pre><code>TASK=$(ouijit task current | jq -r .taskNumber)
ouijit task set-status "$TASK" in_review</code></pre>

        <h2>Hooks</h2>
        <p>
          CRUD for the <a href="#hooks">lifecycle hooks</a>. Hook types are <code>start</code>, <code>continue</code>,
          <code>run</code>, <code>review</code>, <code>cleanup</code>, <code>editor</code>.
        </p>
        <pre><code>ouijit hook list
ouijit hook get start
ouijit hook set start --name "Install &amp; agent" --command 'npm install &amp;&amp; claude "$OUIJIT_TASK_PROMPT"'
ouijit hook delete cleanup</code></pre>

        <h2>Tags</h2>
        <p>Tag tasks for organization in the home view.</p>
        <pre><code>ouijit tag list                               # all tags across projects
ouijit tag list --task 5                      # tags on one task
ouijit tag add 5 bug
ouijit tag remove 5 bug
ouijit tag set 5 bug priority urgent          # replace all tags</code></pre>

        <h2>Scripts</h2>
        <p>
          Scripts are saved shell commands that show up in the runner panel. Set them once, then trigger from the UI or
          the CLI. Unlike hooks, scripts are ad-hoc: they don't fire on lifecycle events.
        </p>
        <pre><code>ouijit script list
ouijit script set --name "Lint" --command "npm run lint"
ouijit script set --name "Tests" --command "npm test"
ouijit script run Lint                        # by name
ouijit script run &lt;id&gt;                        # by id
ouijit script run Tests --task 5              # run inside task 5's worktree
ouijit script delete &lt;id&gt;</code></pre>
        <p>
          <code>script run</code> streams the command's output through your terminal and exits with the command's exit
          code. <code>script set</code> upserts by name, so re-running with the same <code>--name</code> updates the
          existing script's command.
        </p>

        <h2>Plan files</h2>
        <p>
          Each terminal can have a Markdown plan file associated with it. The app shows the plan inline so an agent and
          you can collaborate on a shared TODO list. The CLI is how the agent updates that association.
        </p>
        <pre><code>ouijit plan set ./plan.md                     # uses current OUIJIT_PTY_ID
ouijit plan set ./plan.md pty_abc123          # explicit pty id
ouijit plan get
ouijit plan unset</code></pre>

        <h2>Projects</h2>
        <p>List every project registered with the app. Mostly useful for cross-project automation.</p>
        <pre><code>ouijit project list</code></pre>

        <h2>Environment variables</h2>
        <p>Ouijit sets these on every terminal it spawns. Your scripts and agents can read them directly:</p>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Variable</th><th>What it is</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>OUIJIT_API_URL</code></td><td>Base URL for the local REST API the CLI talks to.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>OUIJIT_API_TOKEN</code></td><td>Bearer token scoped to this terminal session.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>OUIJIT_PTY_ID</code></td><td>Unique id for this terminal session. Used by <code>task current</code> and <code>plan</code>.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>
          Hooks get extra context on top of these. See <a href="#hooks">Hooks → Environment variables</a> for the full
          list of <code>OUIJIT_TASK_*</code> variables available to start, continue, review, and cleanup commands.
        </p>

        <h2>Patterns</h2>
        <h3>Move a task to review when an agent finishes</h3>
        <p>Add this to the end of an agent's workflow to advance the task automatically:</p>
        <pre><code>TASK=$(ouijit task current | jq -r .taskNumber)
ouijit task set-status "$TASK" in_review</code></pre>

        <h3>Tag a task with the language it touches</h3>
        <pre><code>TASK=$(ouijit task current | jq -r .taskNumber)
ouijit tag add "$TASK" typescript</code></pre>

        <h3>Create and start a task in one call</h3>
        <p>The <code>start</code> hook fires immediately, so any agent invocation in that hook runs as part of creation:</p>
        <pre><code>ouijit task create-and-start "Add 2FA" --prompt "Implement TOTP-based 2FA"</code></pre>
      </section>
    </main>
  </div>
</Site>

<script>
  const links = document.querySelectorAll<HTMLAnchorElement>('[data-doc-link]');
  const linkById = new Map<string, HTMLAnchorElement>();
  links.forEach((a) => {
    const id = a.dataset.docLink;
    if (id) linkById.set(id, a);
  });
  const sections = Array.from(linkById.keys())
    .map((id) => document.getElementById(id))
    .filter((el): el is HTMLElement => el !== null);

  const setActive = (id: string) => {
    linkById.forEach((link, key) => link.classList.toggle('active', key === id));
  };

  const observer = new IntersectionObserver(
    (entries) => {
      const visible = entries
        .filter((e) => e.isIntersecting)
        .sort((a, b) => a.boundingClientRect.top - b.boundingClientRect.top);
      if (visible.length > 0) setActive(visible[0].target.id);
    },
    { rootMargin: '-20% 0px -70% 0px', threshold: 0 },
  );
  sections.forEach((s) => observer.observe(s));

  // Initialize active state from current hash, or first section.
  const initial = location.hash.replace('#', '') || sections[0]?.id;
  if (initial) setActive(initial);
</script>
